  <info><![CDATA[# WHAT IS IT?

This is an agent-based model aiming to simulate pedestrian movements on a campus setting road network under winter conditions. It explores how pedestrian route choice behavior forms the pattern of roads walkability, and how the pattern can be changed with snowy road condition and snow-plow clearing strategies.

Pedestrians move between campus buildings along a predefine node-link graph representing the campus network with buildings and roads. Under winter conditions, roads become harder to be walked on, but repeated pedestrians use can increase their walkability. Pedestrians may probabilistically deviate from their shortest path to seek for more walkable routes. Meanwhile, the appearance of snow plow into the network that cleans the snow of roads add even more complexity into the pattern. The patterns of roads walkability and pedestrians average walking time to reach destination can be investigated under various conditions and plow strategies. This model is designed to study how local decentralized decisions by pedestrians and snow plows can affect the system-level emergent outcomes such as the change in walking time and spatial patterns of road usage.

# HOW IT WORKS

## Overview
Goal: Simulating the patterns of pedestrian movement under winter condition; observe patterns changing with snow and plow strategies.

Agent types:
-- Node: Turtles that are not do not make any decision themselves. There are building nodes and road nodes, consisting of the node-link graph. Building nodes have four different types: Academic, Dining, Residential, and Other. Nodes are used as origin and destination for pedestrians, which are selected based on an assigned probability
-- Pedestrians: Agents making autonomous decisions for their movement behavior based on local environment. Pedestrians share the same speed when walking on the same road condition. They have variables tracking their final/temporary destination and their shortest path.
-- Snow Plow: Agents making autonomous decisions based on thier cleaning strategies for their movement behavior. Snow plow is randomly generated any where on the graph. They follow a specific strategy to move between nodes.

Variables:
-- num-ped: Number of pedestrians in the model
-- num-plow: Number of plows in the model
-- speed-ped: the speed of pedestrians movement under normal condition
-- speed-snow: the speed of pedestrians movement under snowy road condition
-- speed-walkable-snow: the speed of pedestrians movement under snowy but more walkable condtion (road with walkability higher than a defined threshold)
-- reroute-p-when-snow: the probability for pedestrians to change their routing and find a more walkable route when meeting snowy road
-- faster-threshold: the threshold of walkability for a road to be with snowy but more walkable condition
-- speed-plow: the speed of plow movement

Behaviors:
Generation of Agents -- Each tick new pedestrian may be generated if the number of existing pedestrian is lower than the defined value.

Movement -- Each tick pedestrians will move toward its targeted node in a certain speed. Plow will also move in a given speed to a selected node.

Route Planning: The origin and final destination are confirmed once a pedestrian is born. Then the pedestrian will use the Dijkstra's Algorithm to search for the shortest path between their origin and final destination and follow the path to move. The principle behind this idea of pedestrians knowing the shortest path is that in a campus setting, pedestrians are mostly students, faculties, staffs who are very familiar with the road network. Unlike some case in urban setting where pedestrians may not know anything about the road network, they live in the network for a long time to know the shortest path between buildings. Therefore, pedestrians in campus setting will follow the shortest path to walk unless other factors like snowy condition motivates them to change to a more walkable road.

Reroute: When pedestrians meet a snowy road, they may probablistically choose to walk on another road with higher walkability. Specifically, once they decide to move to a more walkable road, they will look at all available choices and find the most walkable roads. If more than one most walkable roads exist, they will choose the one closer to their destination. If no more walkable option exist, they will still follow their original path.

Plow Strategy: A general principle is followed by plow under any strategy, which is to choose a path with snow over path without snow. clean-more-walked strategy instructs plow to choose a snowy path that is walked the most (wit higher walkability). clean-less-walked strategy instructs plow to pick a snowy path that is walked the least (with lower walkability).

Spatial-Temporal Scale:
The spatial scale is fixed to the campus scale. The temporal scale is around second to minute level. In fact, the temporal scale can be changed by adjusting the speed of pedestrian. The higher the speed pedestrians have, the larger the temporal scale is. At the default level, with a around 60 ticks average-walking time, assuming that the real-world average walking time is 10 minutes, then the temporal scale can be around 10 seconds.

Process and Scheduling
Each tick pedestrians and plows will decide on where they move and then move. It should be noticed that plows will be only generated after 2000 ticks. This is to make sure that the original pedestrian moving patterns are formed, then introducing plows to see how it can change the pattern of pedestrians movement. Whenever the number of existing pedestrians is lower than the set value, new pedestrians will be generated.

## Design Concepts

-- Emergence
This model focuses on how system-level patterns emerge from many local decisions. Individual pedestrians only respond to their immediate road conditions, and no system-level patterns are explicitly modeled or described. Snow plow also follows simple strategies to determine where to go and clean snow. The emergent patterns arise from the interactions between pedestrians and plows decisions.

-- Stochasticity
Stochastic elements are incoporated at several stages of model. Pedestrians are generated from buildings based on probablistic origin and destination selection. When encountering snowy roads, pedestrians probablistically decide whether to reroute. Snow plow also randomly select road to follow when there are multiple qualifying path available. Interestingly, even with many stochasticity involved in the model, the emergent patterns of pedestrian movement tend to be similar in multiple runs, revealing the fascinating relationship between stochasticity and emergence.

-- Adaptation
Pedestrians adapt their movement behavior based on local road conditions. When snow is present, they may abandon their original shortest path and choose more walkable roads and reroute based on their decision. Another indirect adaptation is that repeated pedestrian usage increases a road's walkability, making it more attractive for future pedestrians. Therefore, future pedestrians movement may adapt to how current pedestrians move.

## Details
-- Initialization
Some parameters, including number of pedestrian, number of plow can be set to any value based on what user want to see. Parameters including pedestrian speed under various conditions, probability to reroute, threshold of walkability to make road faster to be walked are based on studies and developer's judgement.

The complete graph of nodes and links is draw by developer manually. There is simplification that exludes some nodes and path on campus.

# HOW TO USE IT

Press setup and go to run a simulation. Adjust sliders, choosers, and switches to change simulation setting, then press reset-simulation and go to run another simulation.

Basic operation:
-- press setup to import image and graph. The image and complete-graph should be correctly imported directly by pressing setup. If the setup fails to do so, like the graph is not imported, user can press the load-graph button to import by themselves.

-- go: run the simulation

-- reset-simulation: whenever user wants to change the variable setting, they can move the slider then press reset-simulation to setup simulation without reimport image and graph.

-- snowed?: this switch controls whether the simulation is runned under snowed condition.

-- snow-plow?: this switch controls whether to implement snow plow, the number of snow plow to be implemented can be controled by the num-plow slider.

-- show-walkability?: this switch controls the visualization of graph. If the switch is on, the links in the graph will be displayed based on their relative walkability. The more a road is walked, the more black the link will be. When the switch is off the graph will be in normal display.

-- plow-strategy: user can choose different strategy for snow plow to move and observe how their strategies can affect pedestrians moving patterns.

Funtion that may not be necessarily used:
These buttons may only be used if user wants to create graph by themselves.

make-building-node: use mouse to press any part of the image to create a building node.

building-type-to-make: this chooser determine which building type will be made when a building node is created.

making-road-node: use mouse to press any part of the image to create a road node.

make-path: use mouse to select two nodes, a path link will be created between them.

delete-path: use mouse to select two nodes, the path between them will be deleted.

delete-node: use mouse select and delete a node.

save-graph: save your own graph to an external file

load-graph: import graph from an external file


# THINGS TO NOTICE

The average-walking-time monitor keeps tracks of how the average walking time of pedestrians varies. User can observe how this value change over time and under different simulation settings to get a general understanding about how the pedestrians patterns are changed by different conditions and plow strategies.

Switch on show-probability?, user can directly observe which paths are walked more on the graph. Find out how patterns are specifically changes at certain locations under different simulation settings.

In a fixed setting, the patterns of pedestrian movement is relatively stable between ticks and between runs, even with stochastic elements involved.

There are some intuitive and unintuitive changes in average-walking-time and direct visual patterns that can be observed by changing simulation settings.

# THINGS TO TRY

Try switch on/off snow? and snow-plow? to observe how patterns of pedestrian movement change under different conditions.

Select different plow strategies to see how the patterns of pedestrian movement are changed.

Alter the reroute-p-when-snow to see how this probability can affect the entire patterns. Is higher reroute-p-when-snow better or not in terms of average-walking-time? Under what settings for other variables?

Alter the faster-threshold to see how the threshold of walkability to make a road easier to be walked can affect the overall patterns.

Add more snow-plow to see whether it helps to lower average-walking-time or not.

Try different speed combinations, observe how the direct visuals of walkability patterns (with show-walkability? on) changes.

# EXTENDING THE MODEL

More plow strategies can be developed to find more effective way of cleaning snow to lower pedestrians moving time. The interface for plow strategies selection is set to be a chooser for extension purpose. Future user can develop their own strategy and simply add to the chooser to switch between strategies.

A daytime logic can be incorporated. The distributions of origin and final destination of pedestrians can vary in different time of a day. For example, at 12pm and 6pm, people may tend to walk to and from dining buildings.

A snowing condition can be added. Now the model only has snowed condition, which means when snow-plow clean the snow on a road, it won't be snowy again. In snowing condition, road can become snowy again after a certain period of time, making the simulation more realistic.

# NETLOGO FEATURES

-- External file writing, saving and loading. 

-- Include source file: pqueue.nls is included as a source file for the code.

-- Import drawing: import-drawing is used to import image as background

-- Behavior space is used for experiementation. An experiment on testing the effectiveness of snow plow strategies was conducted.

-- Interface with chooser, switch, monitor, button, etc.

# RELATED MODELS

Netlogo Lib: Traffic Models -- Traffic Basic, Traffic Grid, etc.
MiddTraffic Model implemented in class.

# CREDITS AND REFERENCES

Jin, L., Lu, W., & Sun, P. (2022). Preference for street environment based on route choice behavior while walking. Frontiers in Public Health, 10, 880251.
This paper helps me to understand whether and under what condition pedestrians would change their original routing plan. I followed some of its description to build the decision logic for pedestrians to choose a more walkable road

Fossum, M., & Ryeng, E. O. (2022). Pedestrians’ and bicyclists’ route choice during winter conditions. Urban, planning and transport research, 10(1), 38-57.
This paper helps me to determine the default probability of reroute-p-when-snow, as its survey shows how many people may choose to reroute when they meet snowy conditions.

Liang, S., Leng, H., Yuan, Q., Wang, B., & Yuan, C. (2020). How does weather and climate affect pedestrian walking speed during cool and cold seasons in severely cold areas?. Building and environment, 175, 106811.
This paper makes me believe that it is legitimate to think that climate and road condition would change pedestrian moving speed and behaviors.

Ma, L., Brandt, S. A., Seipel, S., & Ma, D. (2024). Simple agents–complex emergent path systems: Agent-based modelling of pedestrian movement. Environment and planning B: Urban analytics and city science, 51(2), 479-495.
This research does not directly support any setup in my model, but it did make me realize that pedestrian movements can itself be a field to work with agent-based model, guiding my direction to decide what to work on for my term project.

In class file: 
MiddTraffic: this model inspired to me about how to implement pedestrian movements on a map. My idea of drawing nodes and links to abstractize map comes from this model.
pqueue.nls: the implementation of priority queue is from this file delievered as part of the alaska island model.


# Responsible Computing
This agent-based model is designed not only as a technical simulation of pedestrian movement but also a simplified representation of how individual decisions (shortest path and reroute), environmental constraints (walkability and snow), and institutional interventions (snow plow with different strategies) interact in shared public spaces. The model highlights how computational tools can be used to explore complex emergent dynamics in spatial explicit systems, while raising questions about assumptions, limitations, and ethical implications.

An important social impact of the model is that it focuses on pedestrians' individual experiences to understand the patterns of overall movement. Rather than directly generating a system-level patterns with mathematical equations, such a way of describing movement patterns can be more realistic and pedestrians benefits driven. By centering pedestrians as agents with limited speed, vulnerability to weather, and imperfect decision-making, the model encourages thinking about walkability, accessibility, and equity in campus and urban design. It demonstrates that how campus issues like poor maintenance of pedestrians infrastructure and inefficient snow-plow assignment and strategies can disproportionally increase walking time and reduce mobility, which in real-world affects individuals with disabilities, injuries, and time constraints.

With real-world data incorporated into the model, it can be used to provide insights on changing campus design, such as add more roads at more concentrated area. Also, institutional interventions and resource allocations can become more efficient with optimized by simulations. This is a low-cost method to improve campus design without taking the risks of causing issues in the real world.

However, at the same time, the user of the model must clearly realize the limitations of the model. First, pedestrians in the model are assumed to have perfect knowledge about the shortest path between buildings, which is unrealistic even in campus setting. Also, the number of pedestrians on campus is not fixed as what is determined in the model. The homogeneity across agents, where they all share similar logic of decision and speed, is highly unrealistic. The actual pedestrians movement decisions are much more complex that no model can accurately model, with various factors, including safety, lighting, crowding, personal preferences, or physical ability. These simplifications mean that the model should not be used for direct policy recommendations without careful validation and extension. 

It should be understood that the limitations of the model do not mean that it is completely useless. Instead, the insights and perspectives it provides are unique and valuable, but only when the user clearly realize the potential biases and assumptions within the model. Agent-based models can create compelling visualizations and numerical outputs that appear authoritative and objective. Without transparency about assumptions and limitations, such models can be misused to justify infrastructure decisions that overlook qualitative human experiences. Responsible computing therefore requires detailed documentation, openness about design choices, and realization of what the model can or cannot explain.



]]></info>
